DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(90)90064-9
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0378426690900649
AB  - The three most widely read Dutch sources of stock recommendations are published weekly. In this paper these weekly recommendations are studied for the period January 1978 until December 1983. Abnormal returns are calculated using the market model as a benchmark. The market index used is the best linear index, which under certain assumptions can be proven to yield the most powerful market model based event study. It turns out that there is no significant long-term abnormal return, although abnormal returns are very significant in the week of publication. These short-term abnormal returns are more pronounced for strong recommendations and for stocks with a small normal daily trading volume. This is very strong evidence for the existence of a so-called ‘self-fulfilling prophecy’.
